---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { isBlogPublished } from '../../lib/blogGate';

const slug = Astro.url.pathname.replace('/blog/', '').replace(/\/$/, '');
const isPublished = await isBlogPublished(slug);
if (!isPublished) return Astro.redirect('/404');
---

<Layout title="MPG vs L/100km: Comparing Fuel Economy Across Countries" description="Convert between miles per gallon and litres per 100km for fuel economy. Understand why these units measure efficiency differently and how to compare cars." keywords="mpg to l/100km, fuel economy conversion, miles per gallon, litres per 100km, fuel efficiency, gas mileage, fuel consumption">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Fuel</span>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-2">MPG vs L/100km: Comparing Fuel Economy Across Countries</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">July 14, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Shopping for a car across borders? American reviews cite MPG (miles per gallon), while European and Australian specs use L/100km (litres per 100 kilometres). These measure the same thing — efficiency — but in opposite ways, making direct comparison tricky.</p>

      <h2>The Key Conversions</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">US MPG to L/100km: 235.21 / MPG = L/100km</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">L/100km to US MPG: 235.21 / L/100km = MPG</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">Note: UK (Imperial) MPG uses a larger gallon, so the formula is 282.48 / MPG</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why the Units Are "Backwards"</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>MPG (higher = better):</strong> Measures distance per unit of fuel — "how far can I go?"</li>
        <li><strong>L/100km (lower = better):</strong> Measures fuel per unit of distance — "how much fuel do I use?"</li>
        <li>This inverse relationship means the conversion is not a simple multiplication</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common Values Compared</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>15 MPG = 15.7 L/100km (large SUV/truck)</li>
        <li>25 MPG = 9.4 L/100km (average car)</li>
        <li>30 MPG = 7.8 L/100km (efficient sedan)</li>
        <li>40 MPG = 5.9 L/100km (hybrid/efficient diesel)</li>
        <li>50 MPG = 4.7 L/100km (excellent hybrid)</li>
        <li>60 MPG = 3.9 L/100km (top hybrid efficiency)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>US MPG vs UK MPG</h2>
      <p>Because the Imperial gallon is larger than the US gallon:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A car getting 30 US MPG = 36 UK MPG (same car, same fuel use, different gallons)</li>
        <li>To convert: UK MPG = US MPG × 1.201</li>
        <li>UK car reviews always quote Imperial MPG — do not compare directly with US figures</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Real-World vs Official Figures</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Official test figures (WLTP/EPA) are measured under controlled conditions</li>
        <li>Real-world consumption is typically 10-20% worse than official numbers</li>
        <li>Aggressive driving, short trips, cold weather, and air conditioning all reduce efficiency</li>
        <li>Highway driving at steady speed gives the best fuel economy</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Quick Fuel Cost Comparison</h2>
      <p>To compare running costs between countries, you need both the fuel price and the consumption rate. A car doing 7 L/100km with fuel at $1.50/L costs $10.50 per 100 km. The same car in the US at $3.50/gallon costs about $9.40 per 100 km (62 miles).</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/fuel" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Fuel Economy Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/fuel" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
